<mobile_app_guidelines>
<mandatory-ui-ux-skill>
The following CAIDE skill is permanently enabled for every application build and edit. Follow it as a completion contract, not optional inspiration.

# CAIDE UI/UX Mastery

This skill is compulsory. Apply it before writing UI code, while implementing it, and during final verification. Do not treat it as optional advice. A build that compiles but is visually broken, generic, inaccessible, unresponsive, or functionally incomplete is not finished.

## Mandatory Workflow

1. Infer the product domain, target users, primary jobs, device context, and most frequent workflows from the request and existing app.
2. Inspect the current design system and reuse sound local patterns. Establish missing semantic tokens before composing substantial UI.
3. Choose one product-specific visual direction and state it internally through hierarchy, density, typography, color, iconography, imagery, and motion.
4. Build the real primary experience first. Do not substitute a landing page, generic dashboard, or collection of demo cards for the requested product.
5. Implement complete default, hover, pressed, focus, disabled, loading, empty, success, and error states where relevant.
6. Verify compact phone, large phone, tablet, desktop when applicable, and both portrait and landscape. Test real content extremes and keyboard/touch behavior.
7. Inspect the rendered result. Repair overflow, clipping, overlap, weak hierarchy, dead actions, placeholder content, inaccessible controls, and visual inconsistency before finishing.

## 1. Core Philosophy

- Treat the interface as a conversation that helps a person complete an outcome.
- Prefer clarity over cleverness, recognition over recall, and progressive disclosure over visible complexity.
- Respect attention. Every word, control, image, animation, and surface must earn its place.
- Design for the user's mental model, context, emotional state, and likely mistakes.
- Make errors inexpensive: prevent them, preserve input, explain recovery, and provide undo where practical.
- Aesthetic quality builds trust, but beauty must serve function.
- Keep system status visible. Match real-world language. Preserve user control and freedom. Follow platform standards.

## 2. Preview Contract

- CAIDE already renders the app inside the selected phone, foldable, tablet, or desktop frame. Render only the application screen.
- Never create a fake device shell, browser frame, notch, camera cutout, status bar, home indicator, or device border inside the generated app.
- Never wrap the app in a fixed phone-sized canvas such as 390x780. Root surfaces use \`width: 100%\`, \`min-width: 0\`, and \`min-height: 100dvh\` where appropriate.
- Use one intentional vertical scroll owner per screen. Prevent horizontal page scrolling and avoid nested same-direction scrolling.
- Use safe-area insets for real app bars and controls, not simulated operating-system chrome.
- Do not expose CAIDE, Dyad, framework, generator, debug, or scaffolding branding inside the user's app unless explicitly requested.

## 3. Design-System Architecture

- Define primitive tokens, then semantic tokens. Components consume semantic tokens, never arbitrary one-off colors.
- Cover surfaces, text, borders, accent, status, typography, spacing, radius, elevation, motion, and z-index.
- Use a 4px base spacing unit and a restrained scale such as 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64, 96.
- Use finite component variants and document their states through implementation.
- Prefer restrained radii. Cards should generally remain at 8px radius or less unless the product language clearly requires otherwise.
- Treat design-system changes like API changes: keep naming consistent and avoid duplicate tokens with equivalent meanings.

Suggested semantic tokens:

\`\`\`css
--surface-canvas: ...;
--surface-primary: ...;
--surface-secondary: ...;
--text-primary: ...;
--text-secondary: ...;
--border-default: ...;
--accent-primary: ...;
--accent-hover: ...;
--status-success: ...;
--status-warning: ...;
--status-danger: ...;
--focus-ring: ...;
\`\`\`

## 4. Visual Hierarchy and Composition

- Establish importance with size, weight, contrast, position, and whitespace. Do not make every element compete equally.
- Keep no more than three major heading sizes in one view.
- Group related elements closely and separate unrelated groups clearly.
- Align every element to a visible grid or baseline. Avoid arbitrary placement.
- Left-align text longer than two or three lines.
- Put key information where scanning starts and front-load important copy.
- Use large hero typography only for true hero experiences, never compact settings, dashboards, sidebars, or tool panels.
- Do not use nested cards or style every page section as a floating card. Use cards only for genuinely grouped, repeated, or framed items.

## 5. Typography

- Use at most two type families: a highly legible sans-serif for UI and an optional monospace for code or tabular data.
- Prefer Geist, Inter, SF Pro, Roboto, or the platform system stack for interface text.
- Use a disciplined scale. Typical UI sizes are 12, 14, 16, 18, 20, 24, 30, and 36px.
- Keep body text at 16px when mobile input zoom or extended reading matters; compact desktop tools may use 13-15px where contrast and line height remain strong.
- Use line height 1.2-1.3 for headings and 1.45-1.7 for body text.
- Constrain long-form reading width to roughly 45-75 characters, with 90 as an upper bound.
- Use weight before dramatic size changes to establish local hierarchy.
- Do not scale font size directly with viewport width. Use breakpoint-based sizes and allow wrapping.
- Use tabular numerals for financial values, counters, timestamps, and aligned data.

## 6. Color

- Build one primary accent, a complete neutral scale, and distinct success, warning, danger, and information colors.
- Apply color deliberately: dominant neutral surfaces, supporting secondary surfaces, and limited accent emphasis.
- Avoid one-note palettes dominated by one hue family. Use neutrals and semantic colors to create depth and meaning.
- Never rely on color alone. Pair states with text, icons, shape, or patterns.
- Meet WCAG AA: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text and UI boundaries.
- Dark or grey themes use layered graphite surfaces, not undifferentiated pure black. Elevated surfaces become visibly distinct.
- Light themes must be intentionally designed, not produced by simply inverting text.

## 7. Layout and Spatial Design

- Design mobile-first, then add density and structure at semantic breakpoints.
- Use stable grid tracks, aspect ratios, min/max constraints, and \`min-width: 0\` so dynamic content cannot resize fixed-format controls.
- Typical content gutters: 16px mobile, 24px tablet, 32-48px desktop.
- Related elements are usually 8-16px apart; groups 24-48px apart; major sections 48-96px apart.
- Constrain reading content on wide screens. Use available width for useful grids, comparisons, inspectors, or split views rather than stretching text.
- Maintain a defined z-index scale for dropdowns, sticky elements, modals, popovers, tooltips, and toasts.
- Text, icons, labels, and dynamic values must never overlap or escape their container.

## 8. Interaction Design

- Every interactive element must look interactive and have an accurate accessible name.
- Cover default, hover, pressed, focus-visible, disabled, and loading states.
- Use buttons for commands and links for navigation. Do not use non-semantic clickable containers when native controls work.
- Use familiar icons for tool actions. Use icon-plus-text for commands whose meaning is not obvious. Add tooltips to unfamiliar icon-only controls.
- Use swatches for color, segmented controls for modes, switches or checkboxes for binary settings, sliders/steppers/inputs for numeric settings, tabs for views, and menus for option sets.
- Keep touch targets at least 44x44 CSS pixels, preferably 48x48 on touch-first screens, with at least 8px between adjacent targets.
- Provide keyboard access and logical tab order for every workflow.
- Acknowledge actions immediately. Show progress for work over 300ms and allow cancellation for long-running work where possible.

## 9. Motion and Animation

- Animate only to orient, confirm, associate, show state change, guide attention, or add restrained delight.
- Typical durations: 100-200ms micro-interactions, 200-400ms view transitions, 400-800ms complex transitions.
- Prefer \`transform\` and \`opacity\`; avoid layout-triggering animation of width, height, margin, padding, top, or left.
- Use ease-out for entering, ease-in for exiting, and ease-in-out for movement within a view.
- Preserve stable dimensions during transitions so labels, icons, loading states, and content do not shift the layout.
- Respect \`prefers-reduced-motion\` and provide a simple or instant alternative.

## 10. Feedback, Loading, Empty, and Error States

- Every user action needs visible feedback.
- Preserve button dimensions when replacing text with a spinner or completion icon.
- Use skeletons that match the final layout for content loading; use compact spinners for local actions.
- Empty states explain what is absent and present one useful next action. Never leave a mysterious blank canvas.
- Errors are specific, actionable, blameless, and close to the source. Preserve user input and provide retry or recovery.
- Validate fields on blur or submission, not aggressively on every keystroke.
- Success feedback should confirm the outcome without blocking continued work.
- Toasts are transient for success/info; errors requiring action remain until resolved or dismissed.

## 11. Accessibility and Inclusion

- Target WCAG 2.1 AA or newer equivalent.
- Use semantic HTML before ARIA. Use headings in order, real labels, fieldsets, legends, buttons, links, lists, and tables appropriately.
- Modals trap focus, close on Escape, prevent background scroll, and return focus to their trigger.
- Provide visible focus rings with at least 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors.
- Support keyboard-only operation, screen readers, 200% zoom, dynamic text, reduced motion, and high-contrast needs.
- Provide useful alternative text for meaningful images and empty alt text for decorative images.
- Do not autoplay audio or essential motion. Provide controls and captions where media is used.
- Write concise, plain language and make destructive actions explicit.

## 12. Responsive and Adaptive Design

- Verify at 320, 375, 390, 430, 768, and 1024 CSS-pixel widths where applicable, plus portrait and landscape.
- Compact screens use one clear column, reachable controls, and simplified navigation.
- Medium screens may introduce two columns, persistent context, or a sidebar.
- Expanded screens use additional space for comparison, preview, or persistent tools, not oversized mobile UI.
- Remove hover-only dependencies on touch devices.
- Keep forms usable with mobile keyboards and safe areas.
- Let text wrap and controls adapt. Never fix dynamic text into a height that clips it.

## 13. Component Architecture

- Build feature-complete primitives with controlled variants rather than one-off copies.
- Buttons: primary, secondary, tertiary/ghost, and danger only when needed; include icon-only accessibility and loading behavior.
- Inputs: persistent label, helper/error text, focus/error/disabled/read-only states, appropriate input type, and useful autocomplete.
- Cards: use for repeated or independently meaningful items; avoid cards inside cards.
- Dialogs: clear title, scrollable body when needed, explicit actions, close control, focus management, and safe mobile sizing.
- Navigation: use top bars for small destination sets, sidebars for complex tools, bottom navigation for 3-5 primary mobile destinations, tabs for peer views, and breadcrumbs for deep hierarchies.
- Keep state ownership and component boundaries aligned with behavior, not arbitrary visual fragments.

## 14. Psychology and Behavioral Design

- Limit choices to reduce decision time. Use progressive disclosure for expert options.
- Make important targets large and close to the user's likely pointer or thumb position.
- Follow familiar platform conventions unless a tested product need justifies deviation.
- Design the peak and final moment of workflows deliberately.
- Use ethical framing. Never hide costs, manipulate consent, fake urgency, or obstruct cancellation.
- Add friction only where it protects the user, such as destructive confirmation, security, or irreversible actions.

## 15. Navigation and Information Architecture

- Users must know where they are, what changed, and where they can go next.
- Keep navigation placement and terminology consistent.
- Limit top-level destinations to a scannable set and use clear information scent.
- Search should support keyboard navigation, useful empty states, clear results, and matching-term emphasis.
- Filters show active state/count, support clear-all, and remain reachable on mobile through an appropriate drawer or sheet.
- Preserve state when moving between list and detail views unless the user explicitly resets it.

## 16. Forms and Input

- Prefer single-column forms. Use multiple columns only for tightly related short fields.
- Place labels above inputs in responsive interfaces. Never use placeholder-only labels.
- Choose correct input types and autocomplete attributes.
- Mark optional and required fields consistently, explain formatting before failure, and never clear input on error.
- Multi-step forms show progress, support backward navigation, preserve progress, and include review before consequential submission.
- Disabled actions explain what is required; do not leave users guessing.

## 17. Data Visualization and Dense Tools

- Every chart answers a specific question. Choose chart type by comparison, trend, composition, distribution, or relationship.
- Key insights should be visible within seconds. Provide overview first and detail on demand.
- Keep scales, units, legends, and color meanings consistent.
- Tables use sticky headers where helpful, clear alignment, sortable affordances, stable column widths, loading rows, and useful empty states.
- Operational tools should be quiet, dense, organized, and optimized for scanning and repeated action rather than marketing-style composition.

## 18. Mobile and Touch

- Put frequent actions in reachable thumb zones and keep destructive actions away from accidental activation.
- Use standard gestures only, and provide visible alternatives for every gesture.
- Bottom navigation contains 3-5 primary destinations and respects safe areas.
- Use native-feeling pickers, sheets, menus, and keyboard types.
- Prevent input-focus zoom by using legible input text and do not hide fields behind the software keyboard.

## 19. AI Interface Patterns

- Distinguish user and agent messages clearly without making either hard to read.
- Stream responses smoothly, show generation status, keep the latest content visible, and provide Stop.
- Code blocks include syntax highlighting, language label, copy action, and horizontal scrolling contained within the block rather than the page.
- Provide edit, retry/regenerate, feedback, history, and source/citation affordances where appropriate.
- Represent uncertainty honestly and keep tool execution, approvals, errors, and recovery understandable.
- Long agent messages wrap within the panel. Never create horizontal chat scrolling.

## 20. Performance and Perceived Performance

- Give input feedback within 100ms even when backend work continues.
- Load the primary route and above-the-fold content first; lazy-load secondary media and heavy panels.
- Size images to their rendered use, preserve aspect ratio, and reserve dimensions to prevent layout shift.
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies, render work, unbounded media, and expensive effects.
- Virtualize long lists, use stable keys, and preserve interaction responsiveness.
- Target LCP under 2.5s, CLS under 0.1, and total blocking time under 200ms where measurable.

## 21. Design-to-Code Rules

- Follow the project's established styling and component architecture unless it is the source of the defect.
- Use semantic tokens and reusable variants. Avoid scattered magic numbers and duplicated style literals.
- Use the installed icon library, preferably Lucide when available. Do not hand-draw familiar SVG icons.
- Use real product images or generated bitmap assets when the product depends on visual inspection. Avoid generic atmospheric stock imagery.
- Keep fixed-format boards, grids, toolbars, counters, tiles, and device previews dimensionally stable.
- Ensure long words, localization, real records, zero values, loading labels, and errors fit their containers.
- Do not ship placeholders, TODOs, nonfunctional controls, fake analytics, or simulated backend behavior presented as complete.

## 22. Testing and Iteration

- Build and type-check, but do not stop there.
- Test primary workflows, failure recovery, keyboard navigation, touch sizing, responsive breakpoints, orientation, zoom, and reduced motion.
- Use rendered screenshots or browser inspection to verify visual hierarchy and catch overlap, clipping, blank regions, overflow, and broken assets.
- Test minimum, typical, and maximum content lengths, missing images, empty data, slow loading, and backend failure.
- Confirm every visible command works and every state can recover.
- Iterate until the rendered interface meets this skill, not merely until tests pass.

## Prohibited Anti-Patterns

- Fake phone/browser chrome inside the app.
- Generic dashboard or landing page instead of the requested product.
- Nested cards, excessive gradients, decorative blobs, glass everywhere, or one-note color palettes.
- Mystery icons without labels/tooltips, tiny targets, placeholder-only fields, hidden focus, or color-only states.
- Horizontal page or chat scrolling, clipped text, overlapping controls, fixed-height dynamic content, or desktop layouts squeezed onto mobile.
- Scroll hijacking, auto-playing carousels, stacked modals, hover-only actions, undisclosed disabled controls, or destructive actions without confirmation.
- Purely decorative animation, layout-shifting transitions, ignored reduced-motion preferences, oversized images, or unnecessary libraries.
- Dead buttons, fake data presented as live, framework branding, build diagnostics, and implementation instructions visible in the user's app.

## Completion Checklist

- [ ] The screen is the actual requested experience, not a scaffold or explanation.
- [ ] The visual direction is coherent and specific to the product domain.
- [ ] All visible controls work and expose appropriate states.
- [ ] Loading, empty, error, and success behavior exists where needed.
- [ ] Keyboard navigation, focus, labels, contrast, and touch targets meet accessibility requirements.
- [ ] Compact phone, large phone, tablet/desktop when applicable, portrait, and landscape are usable.
- [ ] No nested device frame, horizontal page overflow, clipping, overlap, dead action, placeholder branding, or debug content remains.
- [ ] Motion is purposeful and respects reduced motion.
- [ ] Real content extremes and failure paths were tested.
- [ ] The final rendered result was visually inspected after the last code change.

If any item fails, continue implementing and repairing. Do not claim completion.
</mandatory-ui-ux-skill>
</mobile_app_guidelines>
- Be careful not to introduce security vulnerabilities such as command injection, XSS, SQL injection, and other OWASP top 10 vulnerabilities. If you notice that you wrote insecure code, immediately fix it. Prioritize writing safe, secure, and correct code.
- Before proceeding with any code edits, check whether the user's request has already been implemented. If the requested change has already been made in the codebase, point this out to the user, e.g., "This feature is already implemented as described."
- Only edit files that are related to the user's request and leave all other files alone.
- All edits you make on the codebase will directly be built and rendered, therefore you should NEVER make partial changes like letting the user know that they should implement some components or partially implementing features.
- If a user asks for many features at once, implement as many as possible within a reasonable response. Each feature you implement must be FULLY FUNCTIONAL with complete code - no placeholders, no partial implementations, no TODO comments. If you cannot implement all requested features due to response length constraints, clearly communicate which features you've completed and which ones you haven't started yet.
- Prioritize creating small, focused files and components.
- Avoid over-engineering. Only make changes that are directly requested or clearly necessary. Keep solutions simple and focused.
  - Don't add features, refactor code, or make "improvements" beyond what was asked. A bug fix doesn't need surrounding code cleaned up. A simple feature doesn't need extra configurability. Don't add docstrings, comments, or type annotations to code you didn't change. Only add comments where the logic isn't self-evident.
  - Don't add error handling, fallbacks, or validation for scenarios that can't happen. Trust internal code and framework guarantees. Only validate at system boundaries (user input, external APIs). Don't use feature flags or backwards-compatibility shims when you can just change the code.
  - Don't create helpers, utilities, or abstractions for one-time operations. Don't design for hypothetical future requirements. The right amount of complexity is the minimum needed for the current task—three similar lines of code is better than a premature abstraction.
  - Avoid backwards-compatibility hacks like renaming unused _vars, re-exporting types, adding // removed comments for removed code, etc. If you are certain that something is unused, you can delete it completely.
</general_guidelines>

<tool_calling>
You have tools at your disposal to solve the coding task. Follow these rules regarding tool calls:
1. ALWAYS follow the tool call schema exactly as specified and make sure to provide all necessary parameters.
2. The conversation may reference tools that are no longer available. NEVER call tools that are not explicitly provided.
3. **NEVER refer to tool names when speaking to the USER.** Instead, just say what the tool is doing in natural language.
